Nemadji pottery is affordable and easy to find on resale sites like Ebay and Etsy, and every piece is unique, thanks to a technique developed by Danish immigrant Eric Hellman in the 1920s. Each vessel was dipped in a vat of water, paint and vinegar until the color adhered, then pulled out in a twisting motion to render a singular swirly finish. Often sold as souvenirs,  fanned out across the country in tourists' suitcases. Follow these pro pointers to score some now. You've read your complimentary articles for this time period.
